commentText: 1. Don't bad mouth anyone you've worked for (even if it's warranted) 2. Don't be desperate! Don't say "I'll do anything" tell them what you WANT to do for them. 3. Don't JUST answer the question, tell the story. Don't say what you did, say how you did it. 4. Don't say "I don't know how to do that" or "I've never seen that before" rather, say "let me think about that a moment" then connect to something similar. Don't be afraid to circle back to something... once or twice at most. 5. Don't ask them what their company does. You should know the company prior to the interview. Research them in advance. You can, however, ask for details about particular aspects of the company that interests you.

commentText: 1. In almost every interview I've had, I've "complained" about my previous company. Yes manning the job you just left lets the interviewer know you're lying straight through your teeth. You didn't leave the job because life was perfect.  The key is to do so tactfully, tell them exactly what convinced you to leave, or interview for their position over the job you have now. Maybe you weren't getting enough hours, "They didn't have enough work for me, so I'm looking for more." Maybe your boss was an absolute basketcase, "I didn't agree with management well enough to be productive in their environment."   All negative things about your last job can be spun in a neutral/positive way. The key is to not be negative.

commentText: I've only ever had a interview once in my life, it went horrible. I avoid any job that has a traditional interview system, the only reason they want an interview is to see how well you speak and communicate, and to test your confidence. But that basically means the introverts with amazing education & history will be more than likely pushed aside over an extrovert that did well in the interview.   Also the question: Tell me about yourself, needs to be abolished. Work is work, I don't want my employer knowing about my personal life. Everything they need, they already have on the CV that was sent to them.   I get that in certain job roles, the interview makes perfect sense, but say for an example a minimum wage job asking 'why do you want to work for our company over x' is such a dumb question that will always be answered with a lie.

I really loved the founder's vision, and the way he spoke about what we did made it exciting to come to work every day and help make that vision a reality. I ended up getting the job.

commentText: Dear Emma, I found the video you shared to be very useful in providing best practices for ESL speakers during job interviews. I have repeatedly reviewed the behavioral and situational questions you recommended and have found them to be helpful in reinforcing tips such as listening carefully, taking time to organize ideas, practicing beforehand, be specific, drawing from experiences in different fields including volunteering (which I usually never discuss unless asked), and not hesitating to ask politely for clarification if needed. It's also important to control anxiety through meditation and journaling, and to break the ice with small talk at the beginning of the interview. Thank you for sharing this training material.

commentText: As an American Vet myself, I have to say, those videos were disgraceful. To completely politicize your fighting men and women like that is an afront to those who sacrifice and die on behalf of the Country. Over here in America, were fighting like HELL to keep that kind of shit at bay. Its not been an easy battle, even having to go so far as electing Trump to keep it from happening. Now me personally, I dont care if youre Muslim, Gay or Female. It makes no difference to me. What matters to me is your values and your attitude. Are you willing to put your unit and your country ahead of yourself? Are you going to do your job without allowing too much of your personal baggage to get in the way? These videos are preaching the exact opposite. The message here is "regardless of your baggage, well accomodate you." Thats NOT how its supposed to work! Im not saying that the Military should be inflexible or uncompassionate toward their members, not at all. But what I am saying is that those who join, join to SERVE, not to BE SERVED!

commentText: Ex British army soldier here. I am a Nepali Hindu Gurkha who served in the British Army and I am highly disappointed with the UK. Gurkhas have been serving British army for decades & when I got recruited for the Army I was excited but, soon I've realised that UK has forgotten about us or simply ignoring us because Hindus don't go around violently asking for their rights. I couldn't bring my family from Nepal and it was even hard for me to get residency for my wife. I wanted to look after my parents but, we Gurkhas had to fight for our rights despite of dying for this country while people who fought ISIS were welcomed in the UK with all benefits.  Not just Hindu Gurkhas even Sikh soldiers feels like they're being ignored because British army wants to be so sympathetic to the Muslims. I am not asking them to discriminate Muslims but, why are you ignoring us that's all.  Most Hindus don't eat beef but, army canteen seems to have love with Halal food that they forgot that there are more Hindus and Sikhs in the British army than Muslims. Hardly any vegetarian options were available. I personally disliked Halal method of killing animals as I eat chicken sometimes but, I've had no other options but to eat Halal food.  I've stopped working for the army now & new generation Gurkhas are slowly losing interest to join army due to no recognition of Hindus & Gurkhas in the army. I would expect some sort of respect from the government but, no one seems to care.  Our religion don't teach us to spread violence to get an attention but, I just want to ask one question to Briton Do you need a Gurkha who is willing to defend your country or an ISIS supporter who wants to destroy your country ?  When you get the answer for that maybe then you'd realise the value of a soldier who's willing to defend and die for your county.

commentText: I hired my first boat from Anglo Welsh in 1974 and they have been a good company to deal with ever since. It depends what you want, but I can certainly recommend for anyone not that confident that they try the Monmouthshire and Brecon canal (Mon & Brec). It's only 35 miles long and has 6 locks, so you can do the whole length and back in a week relatively easily. It is also beautiful, and because it isn't connected to the rest of the network, it is never too busy. I have had two holidays on the canal and both times hired from Castle Narrowboats who were excellent. You can even hire electric drive boats from them and the canal has charge points along the canal to recharge. Hope this helps someone :)

commentText: Our first hire was from an outfit in Datchet on the Thames opposite Windsor. I well remember it. We'd flown in from Vancouver so jetlagged all to heck. They took us out onto the Thames to make sure we could turn around and then sweetly said Have a nice holiday. We headed up the Thames a couple of hundred yards came around the corner into the first lock and it was jammed with expensive fibreglass cruisers and the lock keeper was happily waving us in. My god, tired, unsure of my ability to steer a steel narrowboat, fear of nailing one of those expensive ones. Ugh! We made it successfully thanks to the lock keeper (it was on the Thames). We moored up right outside the lock on Eton Common (or whatever they called it) and collapsed. We went on to have two of the most enjoyable weeks holidays we've ever had. Everything got easier once we'd slept a bit. And we moored right outside both Windsor Castle and Hampton Court not to mention sundry pubs :) .

videoTitle: Hiring A Business Coach | App Developer UK
videoDescription: "Hiring A Business Coach"- The Daily Overpass #601 Today Eric talks about how "Hiring A Business Coach". Please don't ...
commentText: Hi Eric, great topic. As an old guy I can say I was helped greatly by coaching and mentoring on several levels.  You can skip to the bottom for the punch line . . . . .  When I was young there were customers or people that 'just dropped by' that were older, maybe retired or semi retired and had a vast array of knowledge. I would take 30 minutes or an hour to sit in my office or go and get a cup of coffee to discuss a wide variety of topics a couple times a month. These people were often very intelligent and experienced in many areas. I would save some of my divergent ideas and questions about specific topics for these impromptu sessions. Sometimes you have to be pretty brutal to conserve your own time, but you cannot get sucked into only listening to old 'war stories'.  The second group was kind of a breakfast club that met early Saturday mornings. The people at the table would be business owners of different business types, often millionaires, (back when a million was a big number) and a big dog in their market. (Chicago - South Side) Every Saturday we would solve every problem of the world, including some of our own business problems. These were guys you could call ask about their experience with . . . .? or even something as mundane as getting a new HVAC contractor.  I was in a larger group that met twice a year and we were known unofficially as the 'dirty dozen'. We were the ~12 largest independents in the country but usually not overlapping each other. Because we did not compete with each other, but performed the same services we could share everything we did. These were mostly multi-location, always the largest in their market and often had 50 or more employees. This group could even move the market slightly and often had manufacturers or nation wide retailers as guest speakers.  I also saw a life coach / psychologist for a couple years with great success.   The main point is that you can benefit from a wide variety of groups or services but if you do not benefit greatly within a matter of few hours, drop that one and find something that really works for you.  Doug

commentText: Is a business coach worth it? This is just my take on it... I think it depends on where you are. To me, it probably wouldn't be worth it at this time. This is mainly because the utility function of my money is so high because I don't really have enough of it.  Don't get me wrong I can survive, but hiring a coach would bite too much into my budget at this point.   Having a kind of mentor is something that I can see the benefit in... I don't really know that many entrepreneurial people and I live in a small town at the moment, so I rely on people like yourself, and John Sonmez to kind of be my "coach". I also read a lot, and listen to audio books. Some of the books that I've heard a lot of times that have shifted my perspective on money and business are ''The Millionaire Fastlane" and the "Rich dad poor dad! "books.   Someday, I would love to have a coach or mentor that I could talk with in person, but at the level(pretty low that isüòÇ), I'm currently I think I can get a greater return on my money in other ways.
